2026-05-17 17:08:38 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #8 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_code({"code": "import pandas as pd\n\n# Paths from download path_map\nfrom pathlib import Path\nimport json, os\nMANIFEST = json.load(open('DOWNLOAD_MANIFEST_PATH'))\npath_map = MANIFEST['path_map']\nrc_path = path_map['s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-5/files/radiocarbon_database_regional.xlsx']\nclim_path = path_map['s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-5/files/climateMeasurements.xlsx']\n\n# Read radiocarbon sheet\nrc = pd.read_excel(rc_path, sheet_name='Sheet1')\nprint('Radiocarbon rows:', len(rc))\nprint('Columns:', list(rc.columns))\nprint(rc[['Region','Site','Culture','Material','Species','Latitude','Longitude','Cal. BC 1 sigma']].head())\n\n# Filter for Malta region and Culture Neolithic, Species Homo sapiens\n# Region field may be 'Malta' or 'Malta?' - inspect unique regions\nprint('Unique regions sample:', rc['Region'].unique()[:20])\n\nmalta = rc[rc['Region'].str.contains('Malta', na=False, case=False)]\nprint('Malta rows:', len(malta))\n\n# Filter Neolithic and Homo sapiens\nneol = malta[malta['Culture'].str.contains('Neolithic', na=False, case=False)]\nneol = neol[neol['Species'].str.contains('Homo sapiens', na=False, case=False)]\nprint('Malta Neolithic Homo sapiens rows:', len(neol))\nprint(neol[['Site','Layer/Assemblage/Context','date','Cal. BC 1 sigma','Latitude','Longitude']])\n\n# Determine northernmost sample (max latitude). If tie, choose later calendar year -> interpret 'date' as radiocarbon bp? The instruction: use radiocarbon table to get year. Use 'date' field as year BP? But Gold chain: filter Neolithic, select northernmost sample, breaking ties by the later calendar year. The sheet has 'Cal. BC 1 sigma' which is a range string; we'll try to extract the later (more recent) year from the 1 sigma range's second number.\n# Convert latitude to numeric\nneol['Latitude'] = pd.to_numeric(neol['Latitude'], errors='coerce')\nmax_lat = neol['Latitude'].max()\nprint('Max latitude:', max_lat)\n\ncands = neol[neol['Latitude']==max_lat].copy()\nprint('Candidates at max latitude:', len(cands))\nprint(cands[['Site','date','Cal. BC 1 sigma']])\n\n# For tie-breaking, extract the later calendar year from 'Cal. BC 1 sigma' second number after '-' if possible\nimport re\n\ndef later_year_from_cal(range_str):\n    if pd.isna(range_str):\n        return None\n    # find all four-digit numbers\n    nums = re.findall(r\"(\\d{3,4})\", str(range_str))\n    if len(nums)>=2:\n        # interpret BC years: later year is the smaller absolute BC value? E.g. 6211-6011: later is 6011 (closer to present)\n        try:\n            a=int(nums[0]); b=int(nums[1]);\n            return min(a,b)\n        except:\n            return None\n    return None\n\ncands['later_cal_year_BC'] = cands['Cal. BC 1 sigma'].apply(later_year_from_cal)\nprint(cands[['Site','date','Cal. BC 1 sigma','later_cal_year_BC']])\n\n# If no Cal. BC 1 sigma, fallback to 'date' field (radiocarbon BP), but need conversion. For now pick candidate with max later_cal_year_BC (i.e. most recent)\nsel = cands.sort_values(by=['later_cal_year_BC'], ascending=False).iloc[0]\nprint('Selected sample row:')\nprint(sel[['Site','Layer/Assemblage/Context','date','Latitude','Longitude','Cal. BC 1 sigma','later_cal_year_BC']])\n\n# Determine target calendar year: use selected sample's later_cal_year_BC as calendar year (BC). Convert BC to AD year as negative? Climate ages are in ky (thousands of years) likely relative to present. The climate dataset has 'Age_ky' - in kyr (thousand years). We'll convert sample BC year to years BP and then to ky.\nselected_later_bc = sel['later_cal_year_BC']\nprint('selected_later_bc', selected_later_bc)\n\n# Convert BC to BP: BP = (selected_later_bc) + 1950? Radiocarbon convention: BP is years before 1950. Cal BC year 6000 BC corresponds to 6000 + 1950 = 7950 BP. So BP = BC 